  "prompt": "What is the formula used to calculate thermal energy and how is it calculated?",
  "response": "The formula used to calculate thermal energy (\\( Q \\)) is:\n\n\\[\nQ = mc\\Delta T\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\( Q \\) is the thermal energy absorbed or released (in joules, J).\n- \\( m \\) is the mass of the substance (in kilograms, kg).\n- \\( c \\) is the specific heat capacity of the substance (in joules per kilogram per degree Celsius, J/kg\u00b7\u00b0C).\n- \\( \\Delta T \\) is the change in temperature (in degrees Celsius, \u00b0C).\n\n### Steps to Calculate Thermal Energy:\n1. **Determine the mass (\\( m \\))**: Measure or find the mass of the substance.\n2. **Identify the specific heat capacity (\\( c \\))**: Look up the specific heat capacity of the substance. This value is a material property and represents the amount of energy required to raise the temperature of 1 kg of the substance by 1\u00b0C.\n3. **Calculate the temperature change (\\( \\Delta T \\))**: Subtract the initial temperature (\\( T_i \\)) from the final temperature (\\( T_f \\)):\n   \\[\n   \\Delta T = T_f - T_i\n   \\]\n4. **Plug the values into the formula**: Multiply the mass (\\( m \\)), specific heat capacity (\\( c \\)), and temperature change (\\( \\Delta T \\)) to find the thermal energy (\\( Q \\)).\n\n### Example:\nCalculate the thermal energy required to heat 2 kg of water from 20\u00b0C to 50\u00b0C. The specific heat capacity of water is approximately 4186 J/kg\u00b7\u00b0C.\n\n1. \\( m = 2 \\, \\text{kg} \\)\n2. \\( c = 4186 \\, \\text{J/kg\u00b7\u00b0C} \\)\n3. \\( \\Delta T = 50\u00b0C - 20\u00b0C = 30\u00b0C \\)\n4. \\( Q = (2)(4186)(30) = 251,160 \\, \\text{J} \\)\n\nThus, the thermal energy required is **251,160 joules**.",
